ons for how we understand private property, including Locke, Burke, Marx and Engels. The book looks at how their ideas have been put into practice in ways that continue to shape the modern world, from Harry Truman’s housing policies and the anti-abolitionist George Fitzhugh to Margaret Thatcher and Elon Musk. Arguing that the spectre of ‘the mob’ has been intimately interconnected with the idea of private property throughout capitalist modernity, the book ambitiously narrates this history from the early colonisation of the Americas to Silicon Valley, and the future of human colonisation in space.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPropertyxPhilosophy. 0aPropertyxSocial aspects. 0aRight of property. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAtlantic World.  aCultural History.  aEdmund Burke.  aEnclosures.  aIntellectual History.  aJohn Locke.  aKarl Marx.  aPrivate Property.  aSilicon Valley.  aThatcherism.  aWhiteness.1 aBeatty, Aidan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2023 eBook-Packagez9783111206455oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616571840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526165718423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526165718/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2023